	<div id="id77" class="span-3 sidebar">
		<h3>1 &ndash; 8</h3>
		<div>
			<div id="item-4426" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id78"><p>We are moved in to the new apartment, and someday I&#8217;ll get around to taking pictures of it. I&#8217;m like a kid in a candy store in this kitchen, with more storage and counter space than I ever dreamed of. All I&#8217;ve had time to cook so far was a truly depressing dinner of braised short ribs from Mark Bittman&#8217;s book, for the nice old German ladies who were our first dinner guests last night. I&#8217;m not sure what I did to make the meat so chewy and unappealing, but my guess is that it boiled when I wasn&#8217;t looking, and that that made it toughen up.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Leland</span>
							<span>Oct 3</span>
							<a href="../../../../eat/archive/2007/10/#item-4426">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			
			<div>
				<h3><a class="title" href="../../../../eat/x/mom-is-incredulous/"><span>Mom is incredulous</span></a></h3>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>Oct 3</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div><div>
			
			<div>
				<h3><a class="title" href="../../../../eat/x/spice-market/"><span>Spice Market</span></a></h3>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>Oct 6</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div><div id="id79" class="span-3 sidebar">
		<h3>9 &ndash; 16</h3>
		<div>
			<div id="item-4458" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id7a"><p>If anyone is wondering what I&#8217;m doing in my big new kitchen, the answer is waiting. When I spilled a bit of oil last week and left a dark mark, the landlord informed me that the contractors neglected to seal the new stone countertops. So whatever touches them seeps in, presumably to remain forever. I get nervous even making coffee right now! I think the sealing will happen tomorrow, and then I&#8217;ll be in business 24 hours later.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Leland</span>
							<span>Oct 9</span>
							<a href="../../../../eat/archive/2007/10/#item-4458">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-4459" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id7b"><p>I was happy to learn in my risotto class last night that it is <em>not</em> necessary to stir risotto continuously as it cooks. A periodic stirring to prevent it from burning, which I&#8217;ve always advocated, will suffice. Some risotto luminaries don&#8217;t stir it all! We also learned to make it in a wide sauté pan, rather than the little stockpot I&#8217;ve always used. This of course allows much more liquid to be absorbed, resulting in plumper, more delicious rice.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Leland</span>
							<span>Oct 9</span>
							<a href="../../../../eat/archive/2007/10/#item-4459">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			
			<div>
				<h3><a class="title" href="../../../../eat/x/jamie-olivers-sticky-saucepan-carrots/"><span>Jamie Oliver&#039;s sticky saucepan carrots</span></a></h3>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>Oct 11</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-4506" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id7c"><p>I just had my first trip to <a href="http://nymag.com/listings/restaurant/elis-vinegar-factory01/">Eli&#8217;s Vinegar Factory</a> in Yorkville, and I&#8217;m glad I made it out of there with enough to pay the rent. It&#8217;s the most overpriced grocery store I&#8217;ve ever set foot in. You&#8217;d do better to shop at Dean &amp; DeLuca. Little bunches of herbs for $2.99, heads of lettuce for $3.50, half gallons of milk for $5. I had to get a few things, or else face Pathmark on 125th. But it broke my heart to waste money like that. (Midnight update: just discovered that French green lentils are $1.49 per pound at Fairway. At Eli&#8217;s? $4.99 per pound. They should be ashamed of themselves.)</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Leland</span>
							<span>Oct 13</span>
							<a href="../../../../eat/archive/2007/10/#item-4506">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			
			<div>
				<h3><a class="title" href="../../../../eat/x/mom-clips-recipes-roasts-chicken/"><span>Mom clips recipes, roasts chicken</span></a></h3>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>Oct 14</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-4517" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id7d"><p>In a shocking turn of events, FreshDirect has lowered their minimum order to $30! I guess they were really hurting from the lack of my business over the last several months. This is a smart move: it means I&#8217;ll start ordering every week again, as I imagine many people will. Good going, FD!</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Leland</span>
							<span>Oct 15</span>
							<a href="../../../../eat/archive/2007/10/#item-4517">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div>
	</div><div id="id7e" class="span-3 sidebar">
		<h3>17 &ndash; 24</h3>
		<div>
			
			<div>
				<h3><a class="title" href="../../../../eat/x/braised-cabbage-with-bacon-and-apples/"><span>Braised cabbage with bacon and apples</span></a></h3>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>Oct 17</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div><div>
			
			<div>
				<h3><a class="title" href="../../../../eat/x/mom-muses-on-barbecue/"><span>Mom muses on barbecue, Facebook</span></a></h3>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>Oct 19</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-4551" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id7f"><p>This is what <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth_Reichl">Ruth Reichl</a> said about apple cider molasses in a recent <em>Gourmet Weekly</em> email newsletter I subscribe to, &#8220;Smoky and tart, with deep notes of caramel and balsamic vinegar, it&#8217;s far more complex than your average molasses—but it&#8217;s also far more versatile.&#8221; Doesn&#8217;t that sound delicious? I&#8217;m imagining it brushed onto a grilling pork tenderloin as well as substituting for regular molasses in <a href="http://technically.us/eat/x/mom-makes-gingerbread/">gingerbread</a> or molasses cookies. When I read about it I immediately emailed the buyer at <a href="http://www.mcginnis-sisters.com/">McGinnis Sisters</a> . I heard back from her today and this is what she had to say: &#8220;Hi Rebecca, I have the apple cider molasses coming into the store , due in around nov 1, along with 3 other products that <a href="http://www.allenshillfarm.com/">allenshill farm</a> recomended thanks again for another <span class="caps">GREAT</span> tip.Cheryl&#8221;</p>
<p>And in case you&#8217;re wondering, no, I am <span class="caps">NOT</span> employed by McGinnis Sisters, nor do I accept any &#8220;samples&#8221; from them (although I would if offered!). I simply think it&#8217;s a terrific little grocery store and a great alternative to the big chains.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Mom</span>
							<span>Oct 22</span>
							<a href="../../../../eat/archive/2007/10/#item-4551">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
